There we were, souls and bodies crammed into a Texas church, on the last night of our lives.
Crammed into a room just like this, but with old wooden benches draped in worn red cloth, an organ to my left and a choir behind me, the baptismal font embedded in the wall behind it.
A piece like this, nevertheless.
With the same tremendous sense of suspense, the same deep hopes of salvation, the same sweat in their palms, and the same people deep down who don't listen.
It was December 31, 1999, the night of Christ's Second Coming, and the end of the world as I knew it.
I had turned 12 that year, and I had reached the age of responsibility.
After I stopped complaining about the injustice of Jesus' return when I was to be held accountable for my actions, I realized that it was better for me to clean up quickly.
I went to church as often as I could.
I watched for silence with the anxiety of someone watching for the noise, trying to make sure the Lord hadn't played a trick on me and decided to come back early.
And in case He came back sooner, I had anticipated a backup plan, reading the series of "Left Behind" which was a hit at the time.
I found in their pages that if I wasn't taken away at midnight, I had another chance.
I just had to avoid taking the mark of the beast, fighting demons, plagues and the Antichrist himself.
It would be difficult — but I knew I could do it.
But now was no longer the time to organize.
It was 11:50 p.m.
We had 10 minutes left, and my pastor called us to the altar because he wanted to pray when midnight struck.
Each faction of the congregation took its place.
The choir remained in the choir, the deacons and their wives — or the Baptist bourgeoisie, as I like to call them — stood in the front row in front of the altar.
You see, in the United States, even the Second Coming of Christ has a VIP section.
And just behind the Baptist bourgeoisie were the elderly—those men and women whose backs had once bent under the warm sun of the cotton fields of East Texas, whose skins seemed marked with a smooth and noble brown, just like the clay of East Texas, whose hopes and dreams about the future of their lives outside East Texas had sometimes been shattered.
deeper than their backs.
Yes, these men and women were for me the stars of the show.
They had been waiting for this moment all their lives, as their medieval predecessors had eagerly awaited the end of the world, and as my grandmother had been waiting for the Oprah Winfrey Show on Channel 8, every day, at 4pm.
And as she walked to the altar, I hid behind her, for I was absolutely certain that my grandmother would go to Heaven.
And I thought that if I shook her hand hard during prayer, I might go with her.
So I held his hand, and closed my eyes, to listen, to wait.
The prayers became louder.
And the cries in response to the call to prayer rose even higher.
The organ joined the funeral atmosphere.
And the incipient heat joined with the sweat.
My hand tightens his embrace, so as not to be the one abandoned.
I closed my eyes harder, so as not to see the separation of the wheat from the chaff.
Then a voice rose above us: "Amen."
It was over.
I looked at the clock.
It was past midnight.
I looked at the older believers, whose Savior had not come, who were too proud to show their disappointment, who had believed too much and for too long to begin to doubt now.
But I was upset for them.
They had been deceived, deceived, bamboozled, and I had let myself embark with them.
I had said their prayers, I had not yielded to temptation as best I could.
I had not dipped my head once, but twice, in this baptismal font that gave the break.
I had believed.
And now what?
I arrived home in time to turn on the television and watch Peter Jennings herald the new millennium as he circled the world.
I was struck by the oddity of Jesus' multiple returns, based on different time zones.
And I felt even more ridiculous — hurt, really.
But that night, I couldn't stop believing.
I just began to believe a new thing: that it was possible not to believe.
It was possible that the answers were wrong, that the questions themselves were wrong.
Henceforth, where there had been a mountain of certainty, there was, rushing to its base, a source of doubt, a source that promised rivers.
I can trace the origin of the entire drama of my life that night in this church when my Savior did not come for me; When what I really believed turned out, if not a lie, at least, not quite the truth.
Although some have prepared for the year 2000 in a very different way, I am convinced that you are here because a part of you has done the same thing I have since the beginning of this new century, since my mother left, my father did not return, and my Lord refused to come.
And I reached out, in order to achieve something to believe in.
I stood firm when I arrived at Yale at 18, confident that my trip from Oak Cliff, Texas, was a chance to leave behind all the hardships I had experienced, dreams and broken bodies I had seen.
But when I found myself at home during a winter vacation, face on the ground, hands tied behind my back, and a burglar's gun to my head, I knew that even the best education could not save me.
I held on when I joined Lehman Brothers as an intern in 2008.
So hopeful — that I called my family to inform them that we would never be poor again.
But when I saw this temple of finance crumble before my eyes, I knew that even the best job could not save me.
I stood my ground when I arrived in Washington, as a young employee, who heard a voice from Illinois saying, "We've waited a long time, but with this election, change has come to the United States."
But when Congress came to a standstill, the country was torn apart, hope and change sounded like a joke, I knew that even the second political coming could not save me.
I had faithfully knelt at the altar of the American Dream, praying to the gods of my time, gods of success, money, and power.
But again and again, midnight sounded, and I opened my eyes to see the death of all these gods.
From this cemetery, I began to search once more, not out of courage, but because I knew that either I believed or died.
So I made a pilgrimage, again to another Mecca, Harvard Business School — knowing this time that I couldn't just accept the salvation it claimed to offer.
No, I knew there would be more work to do.
The work started late, in a dark corner of a crowded party, on the night of an early and miserable Cambridge winter, when three friends and I wondered what young people in search of authenticity have been wondering for a very long time: "How about we go on the road?"
We didn't know where to go or how to get there, but we knew we had to.
All our lives, we longed, as Jack Kerouac wrote, to "sneak into the night and disappear somewhere," and go see what everyone was doing all over the country.
Although other voices said that the risk was too great and the evidence too thin, we still left.
We traveled nearly 13,000 miles across America in the summer of 2013, through the pastures of Montana, through the desolation of Detroit, the swamps of New Orleans, where we found and worked with men and women who were creating small businesses whose intention defined the goals.
Having been formed at the western end of capitalism, this appeared to us as a revolutionary idea.
And that idea spread, growing into a non-profit organization, MBAs Across America, a movement that landed me here on this stage today.
This idea developed because we discovered that our generation is hungry for purpose, meaning,
because we found countless entrepreneurs in every corner of America, who were creating jobs, changing lives, and needing a little help.
But if I'm honest, it also developed because I fought for it.
I spared no effort to preach this gospel, to get more people to believe that we could heal the wounds of a broken country, one social enterprise at a time.
But it was this gospel journey that led me to this rather different gospel that I have come to share with you today.
This trip began one evening, nearly a year ago, at the Museum of Natural History in New York, during a gala for Harvard Business School alumni.
Under a replica of a life-size whale, I sat with the titans of our time, as they celebrated their peers and good deeds.
There was pride in a room where the value and net worth under management exceeded $500 billion.
We looked at everything we had done, and that was good.
But as luck would have it, two days later, I had to go not far away, to Harlem. I found myself sitting on an urban farm that had once been a vacant lot, listening to a man named Tony tell me about the children who came here every day.
They all lived below the poverty line.
Many of them carried their belongings in backpacks to avoid losing them in a homeless shelter.
Some of them participated in Tony's program, called Harlem Grown, in order to receive their only meal of the day.
Tony told me that he started Harlem Grown with his retirement money, after 20 years as a taxi driver.
He told me that he was not paying himself because, despite its success, the program was struggling to get resources.
He told me he would accept any help he could get.
And I was there to help.
When I left Tony, I felt the burning and salt of tears coming to my eyes.
I felt the weight of the revelation that I could sit in a room one night where a few hundred people had $500 billion and in another room two days later, just 5 miles away, where a man lived without pay so that a child had his only meal of the day.
It wasn't the glaring inequality that made me want to cry. It wasn't the thought of those hungry, homeless children, it wasn't rage toward the 1% or pity toward the 99%.
No, I was upset because I had finally realized that I was the dialysis of a country that needed a kidney transplant.
I realized that my story replaced all those of those who were expected to take charge of themselves, even if they had nothing to grasp to take charge of themselves; that my organization replaced all the structural, systemic aid that never went to Harlem, or Appalachians or floor -9, that my voice replaced all those voices that seemed too ignorant, too proletarian, too ill-adapted.
And that shame, that shame came over me, like the shame of sitting in front of the television watching Peter Jennings herald the new millennium, again, and again, and again.
I had been duped, deceived, bamboozled.
But this time, the false Savior was me.
You see, I have come a long way from the altar, the night I thought the world was going to end, from a world where people spoke in tongues, regarded suffering as a necessary act of God, and took a text as an infallible truth.
Yes, I've come so far that I'm right where I started.
Because it's just wrong to say that we live in an age of disbelief — no, we believe today just as much as we did before.
Some of us may believe in the prophecy of Brené Brown or Tony Robbins.
We can believe in the bible of the New Yorker or the Harvard Business Review.
We can believe deeply when we worship here at TED Church, but we desperately want to believe, we need to believe.
We speak the language of charismatic leaders who promise to solve all our problems.
We see suffering as a necessary act of capitalism, our god. We take the text of technological progress as the infallible truth.
And we hardly realize the human price we pay, when we fail to question a brick, lest it destroy all our foundations.
But if you are disturbed by the unacceptable things we have come to accept, then it must be time for a questioning.
I don't have a gospel of disruption or innovation, or a triple line of results.
In fact, I do not have a gospel of faith to share with you today.
I have, and offer, a gospel of doubt.
The gospel of doubt does not require that you stop believing, but that you believe in something new: that it is possible not to believe.
It is possible that the answers are wrong, that the questions themselves are wrong.
Yes, the gospel of doubt means that it is possible that we, on this stage, in this room, are wrong.
Because it begs the question, "Why?"
With all the power we hold in our hands, why are people still suffering so much?
This doubt leads me to share that we are putting my organization, MBAs Across America, out of business.
We have fired our team and closed our doors, and we will share our model freely with anyone who grasps the power to do this work without waiting for our permission.
This doubt forces me to give up the role of savior that some expect of me, because there is not enough time and our chances are too slim to wait for seconds, when the truth is that there will be no miracles here.
And this doubt, it regenerates me, it gives me hope, that when our problems overwhelm us, when the paths designed for us seem to lead us to our doom, when our healers do not help our wounds, it will not be our blind faith — no, it will be our humble doubt that will illuminate a little the darkness of our lives and our world,  and will allow us to make our voices heard to whisper,
or to shout, or to put it simply, very simply, "There must be another way."
Thank you.
