Sometimes I feel ashamed to be a European.
Last year, more than a million people in need of our help arrived in Europe and our response was frankly pathetic.
There are so many contradictions.
We mourn the tragic death of two-year-old Alan Kurdi, yet more than 200 children have drowned in the Mediterranean since then.
International treaties recognize that refugees are a collective responsibility, yet we accept that little Lebanon hosts more Syrians than all of Europe combined.
We lament the existence of smugglers, yet we make them the only viable route to seek asylum in Europe.
We lack manpower, yet we are preventing people corresponding to our economic and demographic needs from coming to Europe.
We proclaim our liberal values in opposition to fundamentalist Islam, yet -- we have policies of repression that arrest minor asylum seekers, separate children from their families, and seize refugees' property.
What do we do?
How did we get here, that we adopted such an inhumane response to a humanitarian crisis?
I don't think it's due to a lack of interest, at least I don't want to believe it.
I believe that it is because our politicians do not have a vision, that they do not know how to adapt the international asylum rules, created more than 50 years ago, to globalisation.
I want to step back and ask two fundamental questions, the two questions we all need to ask.
First, why is the current system not working?
Second, how can we fix it?
The current refugee regime was created as a result of the consequences of the Second World War by these people.
Its primary purpose is to ensure that when a state fails, or worse, turns against its people, people have a place to go, to live in safety and dignity until they can return.
It was created precisely for situations such as the current situation in Syria.
Through an international convention signed by 147 governments, the 1951 Convention relating to the Status of Refugees, and an international organization, UNHCR, states have committed to reciprocally admit people fleeing conflict and persecution.
But today, this system is failing.
In theory, refugees have the right to seek asylum.
In practice, our immigration policies block the path to safety.
In theory, refugees have the right to integration or return to their country of origin.
But in practice, they remain stuck in eternal limbo.
In theory, refugees are a global shared responsibility.
In practice, geography means that countries close to conflict host the overwhelming majority of refugees.
The system is not broken because the rules are bad
But because we are not applying them adequately to a changing world, and that is what we need to reconsider.
I will explain how the current system works.
How does the current refugee regime work?
But not from an institutional perspective, rather from the point of view of a refugee.
Imagine a Syrian woman. Let's call her Amira.
For me, Amira represents
A lot of people I met in the area.
Amira, like 25% of the world's refugees, is a woman with children, and she can't go home because she's from this city you see: Homs. A city that was beautiful and historic and is now in ruins.
Amira can't go back.
But Amira has no hope of settling in a third country, because there is a lottery available to only less than 1% of refugees.
Amira and her family face an impossible choice.
They have three options.
The first option is for Amira to take her family to a camp.
In the camp, she could be helped, but there is little future for Amira and her family.
The camps are in austere and arid places, often in the desert.
In the Zaatari camp in Jordan, at night, you hear the shelling from across the border.
Economic activity is restricted.
Education is often of poor quality.
Worldwide, about 80% of refugees in camps must stay there for at least 5 years.
It's a miserable life, and that's probably why, in reality, only 9% of Syrians choose this option.
An alternative for Amira is to head to the urban area of a neighboring country, such as Amman or Beirut.
This is an option chosen by about 75% of Syrian refugees.
But it also has difficulties.
Refugees in such urban areas are often not allowed to work.
They often do not have access to help.
And so when Amira and her family have spent all their savings, they will have nothing left and will be in urban misery.
There is a third possibility that a growing number of Syrians are choosing to choose.
Amira can seek hope for her family by risking their lives on a dangerous and perilous journey to another country, and this is what we see today in Europe.
We therefore offer refugees an almost impossible choice between three options: encampment, urban misery or dangerous travel.
For refugees, that choice is today's refugee regime.
But I believe it is a false choice.
We can reconsider this choice.
The reason we limit these options is because we think they are the only options available to refugees, but they are not.
Politicians see this as a zero-sum problem, if we benefit refugees, citizens pay the price.
We tend to think of refugees as an inevitable cost or burden to society.
But they don't have to be. They can contribute.
My point is that there are ways to increase opportunities and everyone benefits: host countries and communities, our societies and refugees.
And I want to suggest four ways to transform our view of refugees.
These four views have one thing in common: they include the opportunities of globalization, mobility and markets, and modernize the way we think about refugees.
The first idea is that of enabling environments. It starts with the fundamental recognition that refugees are human beings like everyone else, but with extraordinary circumstances.
My Oxford colleagues and I embarked on a research project in Uganda, observing the economic life of refugees.
We chose Uganda, not because it is representative of all host countries.
He is exceptional.
Unlike the majority of host countries, Uganda has provided an economic opportunity for refugees.
It gives them the right to work, the freedom to move.
And the results are extraordinary, for the refugees and for the host community.
In the capital, Kampala, we found that 21% of refugees own a business employing people and 40% of these employees are natives of the host country.
In other words, refugees create work for the citizens of the host country.
Even in the camps, we have discovered extraordinary examples of dynamic and successful businesses.
For example, in a village called Nakivale, we have the example of Congolese refugees running digital music sharing companies.
We found a Rwandan who runs a business to enable young people to play video games on recycled consoles and televisions.
Despite the difficulties of extreme constraints, refugees innovate and the man you see is a Congolese man named Demou-Kay.
Demou-Kay arrived in the camp with very few possessions, but he wanted to become a director.
So, with friends and colleagues, he started a community radio station, rented a camera and made films.
He has directed two documentaries with and for our team and is building a successful business with almost nothing.
These are the kinds of examples that should guide our response to refugees.
Rather than seeing refugees as inevitably dependent on humanitarian aid, we must provide them with the opportunity for human development.
Yes, clothes, blankets, shelter, food are very important in the emergency phase, but we need to go further.
We must offer the opportunity of connectivity, electricity, education, the right to work, access to banks.
Everything we take for granted, that integrates us into the global economy, can and should be offered to refugees.
The second idea I want to talk about is economic zones.
Unfortunately, not all host countries in the world have the approach that Uganda has.
Most host countries do not open their economies to refugees in this way.
But there are always pragmatic options we can use.
Last April, I went to Jordan with my colleague, development economist Paul Collier, and we brainstormed an idea we had there with the international community and the government, an idea to create jobs for Syrians while supporting Jordan's national development strategy.
It is the idea of an economic zone where we could potentially integrate the employment of refugees as well as the employment of natives of the host country.
15 minutes from Zaatari camp, home to 83,000 refugees, is King Hussein Bin Talal's development zone.
The government spent more than $100 million to connect it to the electricity grid and the road network, but two things were missing: access to labour and foreign investment.
so that refugees can work there rather than being stuck in camps, support their families, develop skills through vocational training before returning to Syria.
We recognized that Jordan would benefit, as its development strategy required a shift from a middle-income country to an industrial one.
Refugees would benefit but it would also contribute to the reconstruction of Syria after the war, recognizing that we must incubate refugees because they are the best resource to rebuild Syria.
We published this idea in Foreign Affairs.
King Abdullah took up the idea.
This was announced at the London conference on Syria and a test will begin during the summer.
The third idea I want to put to you is the notion of preference between states and refugees leading to positive outcomes that you see in this selfie featuring Angela Merkel and a Syrian refugee.
We rarely ask refugees what they want, where they want to go, but we can do it and it will be better for everyone.
The economist Alvin Roth developed the idea of market adequacy, where the order of preference of the parties determines their possible correspondence.
My colleagues Will Jones and Alex Teytelboym looked for ways to apply this idea to refugees, to ask refugees to rank destinations, but also to allow states to rank the type of refugees they want based on skills or languages, and then match them.
Of course, there should be quotas for diversity and vulnerability, but this is one way to increase the chances of matching.
The idea of matching is successfully used to, for example, distribute students to university, match kidney donors and patients, and the algorithm exists on dating sites.
Why not apply this to offer refugees choice?
It could also be used at the national level where one of the biggest challenges is persuading local communities to accept refugees.
Currently, in my country, for example, we often send engineers to rural areas and farmers to cities, which makes no sense.
Matching markets make it possible to bring these preferences together and to listen to the needs and demands of the host population and refugees.
The fourth idea I want to talk about is the principle of humanitarian visas.
The tragedies and disorder seen in Europe could have been avoided.
They stem from a fundamental contradiction in European asylum policy: in order to apply for asylum in Europe, you have to arrive spontaneously on a dangerous journey that I have already mentioned.
But why are these trips necessary in the age of low-cost airlines and modern consular means?
These journeys are unnecessary and, last year, they led to the deaths of more than 3,000 people at Europe's borders and on European territory.
If refugees had the right to travel directly and seek asylum in Europe, we would avoid that. And we can do this through humanitarian visas that allow people to get a visa from an embassy or consulate in a neighboring country and then pay for their ferry or plane ride to Europe.
It costs around €1,000 to pay a smuggler from Turkey to the Greek islands.
A low-cost flight from Bodrum to Frankfurt costs €200.
If we allowed refugees, it would have major benefits.
This would save lives, reduce the smugglers' market and mark the end of the disorder seen on the front line of Europe in areas such as the Greek islands.
It is the laws that prevent us from doing so, not a rational solution.
It is an idea that has been applied.
Brazil has taken a forward-thinking approach and more than 2,000 Syrians have obtained humanitarian visas, gone to Brazil and, upon arrival, applied for refugee status.
In this configuration, every Syrian who did this was granted refugee status and was recognized as a refugee.
There is a historical precedent.
Between 1922 and 1942, these Nansen passports were used as travel documents authorizing 450,000 Assyrians, Turks and Chechens to travel to Europe and apply for refugee status elsewhere in Europe.
And Nansen's International Refugee Bureau was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in recognition of this viable strategy.
Each of these four ideas I've presented to you are ways to expand Amira's choices.
These are ways we have to increase refugee choice beyond these options, these three impossible options that I have detailed to you, while benefiting others.
In conclusion, we need a new perspective one that expands refugees' choice but recognizes that they don't have to be a burden.
There is nothing inevitable about refugees being a cost.
Yes, they are a humanitarian responsibility, but they are human beings with skills, talents, aspirations and the ability to contribute, if we allow them to.
In the new world, migration will not stop.
What we have seen in Europe will continue for years.
People will still travel, people will be displaced and we must find rational and realistic ways to manage it, not based on the old logics of humanitarian aid, charity, but built on the opportunities offered by globalisation, markets and mobility.
I urge you to wake up and I urge our politicians to wake up to this challenge.
Thank you very much.
When I was little, I dreamed of the ocean.
A wild place, very colorful and full of life, home to bizarre and fantastic creatures.
I imagined big sharks reigning supreme and graceful sea turtles twirling through the corals.
First as a marine biologist, then as a photographer, I have spent most of my career looking for places as magical as the ones I dreamed of as a child.
As you can see, I started exploring the water very early.
But the first time I really went underwater, I was about 10 years old.
I vividly remember making decided flippers to reach this old cannon embedded in a shallow coral reef.
When I was finally able to catch it, I looked up and found myself surrounded by fish of all the colors of the rainbow.
That day, I fell in love with the ocean.
Thomas Peschak Marine Conservation Photographer In 40 years on Earth, I have had the immense privilege of exploring some of the craziest seascapes for National Geographic and the Save Our Seas Foundation.
I've photographed everything from huge sharks to tiny ones that fit in the palm of my hand.
I felt the fish in the breath of humpback whales feeding next to me in the cold waters of Canada, near the Great Bear Rainforest.
I even knew all about green turtle love rituals in the Mozambique Channel.
We all leave an imprint on the ocean and vice versa.
And the pristine seas I dreamed of as a child are always harder to find.
They are ever smaller and more threatened.
While we humans maintain our role as the largest predator on the planet, I have witnessed direct repercussions and photographed them.
For a long time, I thought I had to shock my audience with disturbing images to get them out of their indifference.
This approach has its merits, but I have come back from it.
In my opinion, the best way to produce change is to sell love.
If you will, I am a couple maker and, as a photographer, I have the unique opportunity to reveal animals and entire ecosystems beneath the surface of the ocean.
You can't love and fight for something if you don't know it exists.
Revealing this – that's the power of marine photography.
Among the hundreds of underwater locations I've seen, a handful of these landscapes touched me deeply.
I saw the first of these landscapes, about 10 years ago, off the rugged and rugged coast of South Africa.
Every summer, huge schools of sardines move north, a mass migration phenomenon called the Sardine Run.
A mad race of these fish
where hordes of hungry and agile predators chase them.
Common dolphins hunt together and manage to isolate sardines from the main school and create small schools.
They dive and trap the fish upwards, against the surface and rush to enjoy their wriggling feast.
Sharks follow closely.
For many people, sharks and dolphins are sworn enemies, but during the Sardine Run, they coexist.
In fact, dolphins help sharks feed more efficiently.
Without dolphins, the small schools created are more sparse and sharks often end up with a "sardine doughnut" or a mouthful of water.
I've had a few lively moments with sharks on the Sardine Run, but I know they don't see me as prey.
I receive blows and am jostled like all the other participants of this brawling banquet.
Let's leave the African coast, to go east, through the vastness of the Indian Ocean to the Maldives, an archipelago of coral islands.
During the monsoon season, manta rays from all over the archipelago travel to a tiny islet of Baa Atoll called Hanifaru.
Armies of crustaceans, most smaller than a marble, are the staple food of manta rays.
When plankton concentrations are low, manta rays feed on their own and they do back, looping pirouettes, like a puppy chasing its tail.
As the density of plankton increases, the lines line up in the tail leu leu and form these long chains. Every delicious bite that escapes the first is swallowed by the second or next.
When the concentration of plankton reaches its peak, the manta rays swim ever closer in a rotating motion by which they feed.
As they swirl through this narrow formation, the column of manta rays creates its own vortex, sucking in and bringing plankton straight into the rays' cavernous mouths.
The experience of diving among these countless rays is absolutely unforgettable.
The first time I photographed Hanifaru, the site was unprotected and threatened by development.
I have worked with NGOs like Manta Trust, and my photos have helped make Hanifaru a marine protected area.
Fishermen from nearby islands hunted these manta rays, they used their skin to make traditional drums.
Today, they are the most fervent conservatives and manta rays contribute more than $8 million to the Maldive economy each year.
I always wanted to go back in time and see an era where maps were incomplete or read, "Here dragons."
I came closest to it by visiting these remote atolls in the heart of the Indian Ocean.
Far, far away, from boat and fishing lines, diving into these waters is a poignant memory of what our oceans once looked like.
Bassas da India is largely unknown. It is a tiny wedge of coral in the Mozambique Channel.
Its barrier forms a shield that protects its inner lagoon, a nursery for Galapagos sharks.
These sharks are anything but shy, even during the day.
Something told me that they would be even bolder and more numerous at night.
I found myself facing more sharks than ever before, gathered on a simple outcrop.
Photographing and sharing moments like these reminds me why I chose this path.
Not long ago, I was working on a project in Baja California for National Geographic.
Halfway, descending along the Pacific coast, is San Ignacio Lagoon, where the gray whale comes to give birth.
For a century, this coast was the scene of a systematic massacre, more than 20,000 gray whales were killed, leaving only a few hundred to survive.
Today, the descendants of these same whales play on the surface with their offspring and they even interact with us.
This species has done remarkably.
On the other side of the peninsula is Cabo Pulmo, a sleepy fishing village.
Decades of overfishing have brought them to the brink of collapse.
In 1995, local fishermen convinced the authorities to make their waters a marine reserve.
But what happened next is a miracle.
In 2005, after only a decade of protection, scientists recorded the largest increase in fish.
But don't take my word for it, come with me.
In a breath, swim into the depths with me in the middle of one of the largest and densest schools of fish I've ever encountered.
We all have the opportunity to inspire hope.
And through my photos, I would like to convey the message that it is not too late for our oceans.
And I would particularly like to highlight nature's resilience in the face of 7.3 billion people.
My hope is that in the future, I will have to search hard to make photos like this, while creating images that show our respectful coexistence with the ocean that,
I hope, will become the daily life for me.
To thrive and survive doing my job, you really have to be a foolproof optimist.
I always work thinking that the next fabulous image that will serve my purpose is ready, just behind the next reef, in the heart of the next lagoon, or who knows, maybe in the next one.
When I moved to Harare in 1985, social justice was at the heart of Zimbabwe's national health policy.
The new government was emerging from a long war of independence and immediately announced a socialist program: health services, primary education became essentially free.
A major expansion of rural health centers has placed about 80% of the population within a two-hour walk of one of these centers, a truly remarkable achievement.
In 1980, the year of independence, 25% of Zimbabwe's children were fully immunized.
In 1990, a decade later, this proportion was 80%.
I felt extremely privileged to be part of this transformation, a revolution.
The excitement, the camaraderie was palpable.
Working with brilliant Zimbabweans—scientists, doctors, activists—I felt connected not only to an African independence movement, but to a progressive global movement for public health.
But there were considerable challenges.
Zimbabwe reported its first case of AIDS in 1985, the year I arrived.
I had taken care of a few AIDS patients in the early '80s, during my medical training at the hospital in Harlem, but — we had no idea what was in store for Africa.
My first days there, the infection rate was 2%.
It would skyrocket to one in four adults by the time I left Harare 17 years later.
In the mid-90s, I told hundreds of prime-age people they had HIV.
I had seen friends and colleagues, my students, patients die in the hospital.
In response, my colleagues and I set up a clinic.
We were demonstrating condom use.
We have launched education in schools, interventions in the workplace.
We were doing research. We gave advice to partners of infected men so that they knew how to protect themselves.
We worked hard, and at the time, I thought I was doing my best.
I provided excellent treatment, as good as possible.
But I wasn't talking about structural change.
Former UN Secretary Kofi Annan spoke honestly about his personal failure that led to the Rwandan genocide.
In 1994, he was the director of the UN Peace Department.
At a memorial 10 years later, he said, "At the time, I thought I was doing my best, but I realized after the genocide that I could and should have done more to sound the alarm and gather support."
The AIDS epidemic took the health community by surprise, and today, when the World Health Organization estimates that 39 million people have died from the disease, I am not alone in remorse and regret for not having done more, sooner.
But when I lived in Zimbabwe, I didn't see my role as that of an advocate or a politician.
I was there because of my technical skills, clinical skills and epidemiological research.
For me, my job was to take care of patients and do research to better understand transmission patterns in the population, and I hoped we would slow the spread of the virus.
I was aware that marginal populations were at very high risk of having and dying from AIDS.
And on sugar plantations, which closely resembled feudal fiefdoms more than any modern business, 60 percent of pregnant women had HIV.
I worked to show that being infected was not a moral failure but rather linked to a culture of male superiority, forced immigrant labor and colonialism.
Whites were largely spared.
As health professionals, our tools were pitifully weak: imploring people to change their individual behavior, to use condoms, to reduce the number of partners.
Infection rates were rising. And when a treatment became available in the West, which remained our most powerful weapon against the virus, it was not affordable for the African public sector.
I did not speak out against the unequal access to these life-saving drugs or the underlying economic and political systems that drive up infection rates among large groups of the population.
I rationalized my silence by telling myself that I was just a visitor to this country, that sounding the alarm could get me expelled, prevented me from doing my job, from taking care of my patients, from doing much-needed research.
So I didn't revolt against the government's initial position on AIDS.
I did not express my concerns out loud.
Many doctors and health professionals may think I didn't do anything wrong.
Our pact with our patients, the Hippocratic Oath and its variants, evokes the inviolability of the patient-doctor relationship.
I did everything I could for every patient I had.
But I knew that epidemics appear along the fissures in our society, reflecting not only our biology, but more notably patterns of marginalization, exclusion, discrimination related to race, gender, sexuality, class, etc.
This was true for AIDS.
This was true recently for Ebola.
Medical anthropologists like Paul Farmer, who worked on AIDS in Haiti, have called this "structural violence." Structural because inequalities are embedded in the political and economic organization of our social world, and are often invisible to privileged people and those in power; and violence because its impact — premature deaths, suffering, disease — is violent.
We do little for our patients if we do not recognize these social injustices.
Sounding the alarm is the first step towards good public health practice, and this is how we could gather support to revolutionize and create change together.
Today, I do not remain silent.
I talk about many things, even if they make those who listen to them uncomfortable, even if they make me uncomfortable.
A lot of what I say has to do with racial differences and institutionalized racism, things that are no longer supposed to exist in this country, let alone in medical practice or public health.
But they exist and we pay for them by shortening lives.
That's why sounding the alarm about the impact of racism on health in the United States, the current institutional and interpersonal violence faced by people of color, mixed with our sad legacy of 250 years of slavery, 90 years of Jim Crow and 60 years of imperfect equality, sounding the alarm about it is fundamental to the successful completion of my work as New York City Health Commissioner.
In New York City, premature mortality — dying before age 65 — is 50 percent higher for black men than for whites.
In 2012, a black woman was 10 times more likely than a white woman to die in childbirth.
Although we have made tremendous strides in reducing infant mortality rates, a black baby is still nearly three times more likely than a white baby to die in its first year.
New York is no exception.
These statistics are compared with statistics made across the United States.
A recent analysis by the New York Times reported that there were
1.5 million black men missing. They cited the fact that more than one in six black men who are now between the ages of 25 and 54 no longer lead a normal life, but were in prison or died prematurely.
There is a great injustice in the face of the daily and disproportionate violence against young black men, which is the focus of the recent #BlackLivesMatter protests.
But we must remember that the disparate rates that persist and the occurrence and outcome of common diseases — heart disease, cancer, diabetes, HIV — diseases that can kill gently and silently and take even more black lives prematurely.
When the #BlackLivesMatter movement took shape, I was frustrated and angry that the medical community was reluctant to use the word "racism" in our research and work.
You must have felt something every time I said it.
Our students have participated in demonstrations in white coats, but the medical community has mostly stayed away as current discrimination continues to affect disease patterns and mortality.
And I am afraid that the trend of personalized and precise medicine, the search for biological or genetic targets for a more appropriate treatment, could inadvertently make us lose sight of the global situation, that is, the daily context, where a person lives, grows, works, loves, a fundamental factor in determining the health of the population:  For too many of us, poor health.
As health professionals, in our daily work, whether in practice or in research, we witness a great injustice: homeless people who are unable to follow medical advice because they have other priorities; transgender youth who think about suicide because our society is too rigid; the single mother who is made to feel responsible for the poor state of health of her child.
Our role as healthcare professionals is not just to treat our patients but to sound the alarm and promote change.
Whether by law or not, our position in society makes us very credible and we should not spoil that.
I regret not speaking out in Zimbabwe, and I promised myself that as New York City's Health Commissioner, I would use every opportunity I could to sound the alarm and gain support for health equity.
I will speak out against racism, and I hope you will join me, and I will join you in denouncing sexism or any other form of inequality.
It is time to stand up and, as a community, speak out against structural inequalities.
We don't need to have all the answers to call for change.
We just need courage.
The health of our patients, of each and every one of us, depends on it.
A show of hands: How many of you have ever deleted a Facebook friend because he made an offensive remark about politics, religion, parenting, food?
How many of you avoid at least one person just so you don't have to talk to them?
Before, to have a polite conversation, we followed Henry Higgins' advice in "My Fair Lady": stick to the weather and your health.
But these days, with climate change and the anti-vaccination movement, these topics... are no longer very safe.
The world we live in, this world where any conversation can potentially turn into controversy, where our politicians cannot talk to each other, and where even the most trivial topics have supporters and detractors, this world is not normal.
Pew Research did a study of 10,000 American adults and found that, right now, we are more polarized, more divided, than ever before.
We make fewer compromises, which means we don't listen to each other.
We decide where to live, who to marry and even who will be our friends, based on our already established convictions.
Again, that doesn't mean we don't listen to each other.
A conversation requires a balance between talking and listening, and somewhere along the way, we've lost that balance.
This is partly due to technology.
The laptops you all have, either in your hands or close enough to be able to grab them quickly.
According to Pew Research, about one-third of American teens send more than 100 text messages a day.
Many of them, the majority in fact, will probably text their friends rather than talk to them face-to-face.
There is a great article in "The Atlantic" magazine.
written by Paul Barnwell, a high school teacher.
His students did a communication project.
He wanted to teach them how to talk about a particular topic without notes.
He said, "I realized... »
"I realized that the ability to hold a conversation is perhaps the skill most neglected to teach.
Children spend hours talking and brainstorming through screens, but they rarely have the opportunity to hone their interpersonal communication skills.
It may sound weird, but we have to ask ourselves: in the twenty-first century, what skill is more important than knowing how to have a coherent conversation?
My job is to talk to people: Nobel laureates, truck drivers, billionaires, kindergarten teachers, heads of state, plumbers.
I talk to people I like and others I don't.
I talk to people with whom I deeply disagree.
But I always have fantastic conversations with them.
For the next 10 minutes, I would like to teach you how to speak and listen.
Many of you have already heard advice on this subject: look people in the eye, think beforehand about interesting topics to discuss, look, nod and smile to show your attention, repeat what you have heard or summarize it.
Forget all that.
It's crap.
There is no reason to learn to demonstrate that you are attentive, if you are indeed attentive.
I use exactly the same skills as a professional interviewer as in my daily life.
So I'm going to teach you how to question people and it's going to help you learn how to be better communicators.
Learn to have a conversation without wasting your time, without getting bored, and most importantly, without offending anyone.
We've all had extraordinary conversations before.
We have had them. We know what it is.
The kind of conversation that makes you feel involved and inspired, or that makes you feel like you've really bonded, or been fully understood.
There's no reason why the majority of our conversations shouldn't be this way.
I have 10 ground rules. I'll explain them to you but honestly, if you take one and master it fully, you'll already have better conversations.
Number 1: No multitasking.
Not just putting down your laptop, tablet or car keys, or whatever you have in hand.
Be present.
Live in the moment.
Don't think about arguing with your boss,
nor what you're going to eat tonight.
If you want to end the conversation, do it, but don't just be half present.
Number 2: Don't teach a lesson.
If you want to give your opinion, without any opportunity to respond, discuss, react or grow, write a blog.
I have a very good reason not to invite critics to my show: they are very boring.
Conservatives will hate Obama, food stamps and abortion.
The Liberals will hate the big banks, the oil industry and Dick Cheney.
Completely predictable.
You don't want to be like that.
You have to start every conversation, with the idea that you are going to learn something.
Scott Peck, the famous therapist, said that for true listening, you have to erase yourself.
Sometimes it means setting aside your own opinion.
He said that the speaker will feel this acceptance, and become less and less vulnerable and more likely offer the hidden recesses of his mind to the listener.
Consider that you have things to learn.
Bill Nye: "Every person knows something you don't."
I put it this way: every person is an expert in something.
Number 3: Ask open-ended questions.
For that, take inspiration from journalists.
Start your questions with who, what, when, where, why or how.
If you ask a complex question, the answer will be simple.
If I ask you, "Were you terrified?"
You will answer the most powerful word in this sentence, here "terrified", and the answer will be yes or no.
"Were you angry?" "Yes, very angry."
Let them describe. They are the ones who know.
Ask questions such as, "What was it like?"
"How did you feel?"
Because they might need a moment of reflection and then you will have a much more interesting answer.
Number 4: Go with the flow.
It means that ideas will come to your mind and you have to let them come out of your mind.
We have often heard interviews where the guest speaks for several minutes, and then the host takes the floor and asks a question that seems to come out of nowhere, or that has already been answered.
The host probably stopped listening 2 minutes before because he was thinking about his next question, a very smart question he was determined to ask.
We do the same thing.
We're sitting and chatting with someone, and then we remember meeting Hugh Jackman in a coffee shop.
We stop listening.
Stories and ideas will come to you.
You have to let them come and then leave.
Number 5: If you don't know, say you don't know.
People on radio, especially on NPR, are more aware that what they say is being recorded; They are therefore more cautious when talking about their expertise and what they are sure they know.
Do the same. Fish out of the extra room of caution.
The floor should not be taken lightly.
Number 6: Don't compare your experience to theirs.
If they're talking about the loss of a family member, don't talk about the loss of a family member.
If they talk about the problems they have at work, don't tell them you hate your job.
It's not the same, ever.
Every experience is unique.
Most importantly, it's not about you.
No need to use this moment to prove that you are awesome or how much you have suffered.
Someone asked Stephen Hawking for his IQ, who replied, "No idea. Those who boast about their IQ are dummies. »
Conversations are not promotional opportunities.
Number 7: Try not to repeat yourself.
It's condescending and very boring and we tend to do it.
Especially during conversations at work, or with our children, we have a message to pass on so we rephrase it tirelessly.
Don't do it.
Number 8: Save the details.
Frankly, it doesn't matter what years, names, dates and all those details you can't remember.
I don't care. What matters is you.
People are interested in you, in what you have in common.
Forget the details. Leave them out.
Number 9: it's not the last, but it's the most important.
Listen.
I can't tell you how many important people have said that listening is perhaps the most important skill to develop.
Buddha said, and I paraphrase, "If your mouth is open, you don't learn."
And Calvin Collidge said, "No one has ever been fired for listening."
Why don't we listen to each other?
First, we prefer to talk.
When I speak, I am in control.
I don't have to hear what I'm not interested in.
I am the center of attention.
I can put forward my identity.
But it's not just that: we get distracted.
We speak an average of 225 words per minute, but can listen to up to 500.
So our minds complete with another 275 words.
I know it takes effort and energy to give your attention to someone, but if you don't, it's not a conversation.
but rather two people shouting barely related sentences in the same place.
You have to listen to each other.
Stephen Covey put it very well:
"Many of us don't listen to understand.
We listen to respond. »
One last rule, number 10: be brief.
[A good conversation is like a miniskirt: short enough to hold attention, and long enough to cover the subject. "My sister] It all comes down to a basic concept: take an interest in others.
I grew up with a very famous grandfather and there was a ritual in my house.
People would come and talk to my grandparents and after they left, my mom would come up to us and say, "You know who it was?
She was the finalist of Miss America.
He was the mayor of Sacramento.
She won a Pulitzer Prize. He is a Russian ballet dancer. »
So I grew up believing that everyone has a hidden and absolutely awesome side.
I think that makes me a better facilitator.
I keep my mouth shut as much as possible, keep an open mind and am always ready to be amazed and never disappointed.
Do the same.
Go talk to people, listen to them, and, most importantly, be prepared to be amazed.
Thank you.
Hello.
My name is Matthew Williams, and I'm a champion.
I won medals in three different sports and national championships in Canada, played basketball at an international level and was proud to represent Canada on the world stage.
I train 5 days a week in basketball and speed skating, working with high quality coaches and mental performance consultants to be the best in my sport.
Besides, I do all this with the Special Olympics.
Does it change the way you perceive me and my successes?
The world doesn't see people like me as champions.
Not so long ago, people like me were on the run and hidden.
Special Olympics have come a long way since the beginning in 1968, but too often people with intellectual disabilities are invisible to the general public.
People use the "R" word with me, and they think it's okay.
It is the word "delayed" or "backlog" used in a derogatory way.
They have no idea how much it hurts me and my friends.
I don't want you to think I'm here for charity.
I am here because there is always a big problem with the way many people perceive individuals with intellectual disabilities, or, too often, the way they do not see them at all.
Did you know that the World Championships took place this year?
I was one of more than 6,500 athletes with intellectual disabilities from 165 countries competing in Los Angeles.
There were more than 62,000 spectators at the opening ceremonies, and there was TSN and ESPN covering the event.
Did you know that this event took place?
What do you think when you meet someone like me?
I am here today to challenge you to consider us equals.
Special Olympics transforms the unique identity of athletes with intellectual disabilities and the perception of anyone watching the competition.
For those of you who don't know, Special Olympics is for athletes with intellectual disabilities.
Special Olympics are separate from Paralympic and Olympic Games.
We offer high-quality, year-round sports programs for people with intellectual disabilities, which changes lives and perceptions.
This movement has changed my life and the lives of so many others.
And it has changed the way the world views people with intellectual disabilities.
I was born epileptic and with an intellectual disability.
Growing up, I played hockey until I was 12.
The older I got, the harder I felt was to keep up with others, and I became upset and frustrated.
For a while, I didn't play any sports, had no friends, and felt forgotten and sad.
There was a time when people with intellectual disabilities were hidden from society.
No one thought they could play sports, let alone be an important member of society.
In the 60s, Dr. Frank Hayden, a scientist at the University of Toronto, was studying the effects of regular exercise on the fitness of children with intellectual disabilities.
Using rigorous scientific research, Dr. Hayden and other researchers concluded that it was simply the lack of opportunity to participate that led to fitness problems.
Many people doubted that people with developmental disabilities could benefit from fitness programs and sports competitions.
But pioneers like Dr. Hayden and Eunice Kennedy Shriver, the founder of Special Olympics, persevered, and Special Olympics athletes proved them right four and a half million times.
Before I joined Special Olympics, I was nervous because I was young, shy, had little confidence and didn't have many friends.
When I arrived, however, everyone encouraged me a lot, supported me and let me be myself without being judged.
Now I am a basketball player and speed skater who competed at regional, national games, and this year ended up at the World Summer Games in Los Angeles, where I was part of the very first Canadian basketball team to compete at the World Games.
I'm one of more than four and a half million athletes around the world, and I've heard so many similar stories.
Being a Special Olympics athlete brings pride and dignity.
Special Olympics also address important health needs.
Studies have indicated that, on average, men with intellectual disabilities die 13 years younger than men without, and women with intellectual disabilities die 20 years younger than women without.
Special Olympics keeps us healthy by getting us active and participating in sport.
In addition, our coaches teach us about nutrition and health.
Special Olympics also provides free screening tests for athletes who have difficulty communicating with their doctor or accessing medical care.
At the 2015 World Summer Games, my Team Canada teammates and I played against Team Nigeria.
The day before our match, the Nigerian basketball team had come to the screening of World Games athletes were distributed free of charge to seven out of ten members and had the opportunity to hear clearly for the first time.
This change for them was incredible.
They were very excited, happy and confident, because their coaches could communicate orally with them.
And they were very emotional because they could hear the sounds of the basketball, the sounds of the whistle and the enthusiastic fans in the stands — sounds that we take for granted.
Special Olympics does more than transform athletes in sport.
The Special Olympics transforms their lives off the field.
This year, research showed that nearly half of adults in the U.S. don't know a single person with an intellectual disability, and the 44 percent of Americans who don't have personal contact with intellectual disabilities are significantly less tolerant and positive.
Then there's the "R" word, demonstrating that people with intellectual disabilities are still invisible to far too many people.
People use it as a usual term or an insult.
It was tweeted more than nine million times last year, and it's deeply hurtful to me and my four and a half million fellow athletes around the world.
People don't think it's insulting, but it is.
As fellow athlete and world spokesperson John Franklin Stephens wrote in an open letter to a political commentator who used the "R" word as an insult, "Come join us one day at the Special Olympics.
You will see if you leave with the heart unchanged. »
This year, at the 2015 World Summer Games, people lined up for hours before diving into the final night of weightlifting competition.
It was a sold-out night when my teammate Jackie Barrett, the Newfoundland Elk, lifted 297kg and 277kg in squats — setting huge new Special Olympics records.
Jackie is one of the record holders among all weightlifters in Newfoundland — not just at Special Olympics but all weightlifters.
Jackie was a huge celebrity in Los Angeles, and ESPN live-tweeted her new record and was impressed with her performance.
50 years ago, few people imagined mentally disabled people capable of doing something like this.
This year, 60,000 spectators filled the famous LA Memorial Coliseum to watch the opening ceremonies of the World Games and applaud athletes from 165 countries around the world.
Far from being hidden, we were applauded and celebrated.
Special Olympics teach athletes to be confident and proud of themselves.
Special Olympics teaches the world that people with intellectual disabilities deserve respect and consideration.
Now I have dreams and successes in my sport, great coaches, respect and dignity, better health, and pursuing a career as a personal trainer.
I'm no longer hidden, mocked, and I'm here giving a TED talk.
The world is a different place because of Special Olympics, but there is still work to be done.
So the next time you see someone with intellectual disabilities, I hope you see their talent.
The next time someone uses the "R" word next to you, I hope you'll tell them how hurtful it is.
I hope you'll consider getting involved in the Special Olympics.
I would like to leave you with one last thought.
Nelson Mandela said, "Sport has the power to change the world."
Special Olympics are changing the world by transforming four and a half million athletes and giving us a place to trust, meet friends, not be judged and feel and be champions.
Thank you very much.
You probably don't know Kenema in Sierra Leone, or Arua in Nigeria.
For me these are the two most extraordinary places on Earth.
There, in hospitals, there is a community of nurses, doctors and scientists who have calmly fought one of humanity's deadliest threats in years: the Lassa virus.
The Lassa virus resembles the Ebola virus.
It can cause a high fever and can often be fatal.
But these people risk their lives every day, to protect individuals in their communities, and ultimately to protect us all.
One of the most amazing things I learned about them, during one of my first visits, a long time ago, was that they start every morning – those difficult mornings on the front lines – singing.
They come together, and they show their joy and strength.
Over the years, we have visited each other. I could be among them, sing, and write. It was extraordinary, because it reminds us that we are not just here for science, but that we are bound together by a shared humanity.
You can imagine, it is extremely important, even vital, when things started to change.
The situation changed in March 2014, when the Ebola outbreak was declared in Guinea.
It was the first outbreak in West Africa, near the border of Sierra Leone and Liberia.
It was scary... We were all terrified.
We had suspected for some time that the Lassa and Ebola viruses were more prevalent than previously thought, that it could reach Kenema.
So members of my team immediately joined Dr. Humarr Khan and his team on the ground. We have set up diagnostics to perform molecular tests capable of detecting the arrival of Ebola in Sierra Leone.
We had already managed to control the Lassa virus. We knew how to do it, the team was outstanding.
We just had to give them the tools and the lab for Ebola.
Unfortunately, that day has arrived.
On 23 May 2014, a woman arrived in the maternity ward of the hospital. The team performed molecular testing and identified the first case of Ebola virus in Sierra Leone.
It was an exceptional job.
They were able to diagnose the case immediately, treat the patient safely, and begin to understand what was going on.
It could have prevented what happened.
But the day it happened, the epidemic had been brewing for several months.
There were already hundreds of cases, surpassing all previous outbreaks.
It entered Sierra Leone, not as a singular case, but as a tidal wave.
We worked with the international community, the Ministry of Health, with Kenema, to deal with the cases. The next week there were 31, then 92, then 147 cases, they all came to Kenema, one of the only places in Sierra Leone that could solve this problem.
We worked tirelessly, trying everything we could to help each person, and try to get attention. We also did something else:
we didn't throw away the blood tests, used to detect Ebola, we put them in a chemical to turn them off. We packed them and shipped them across the ocean.
We sent them to Boston, where my team works.
We also worked, tirelessly, day after day. We quickly generated 99 Ebola virus genomes.
The genome is the architect's plan of a virus.
We all have one.
It indicates what we are made of, and gives us so much information about ourselves.
The results of this kind of work are simple and very useful.
We took these 99 different viruses, we observed and compared them, and we found that, by comparing them to the three genomes that had been previously published in Guinea, the epidemic had emerged in Guinea several months earlier, and that, once in humans, it was transmitted from human to human.
This is very important when determining how to intervene, because contact tracing is paramount.
The virus has also been found to mutate as it moves between humans.
Every mutation is important because diagnostics, vaccines, and our therapies are all based on genome sequence. This is the guide.
Global health experts need to respond, develop and recalibrate all their work accordingly.
But science doesn't work that way. My position at the time was that I had the data and I could have worked in silos for months, analyzed the data carefully, slowly, submitted an article for publication, made some changes, and finally published my data after the official release.
This is how the status quo in science works.
This time, there is no question of doing so.
We had friends on the ground. For us, it was obvious that we needed help, a lot of help ...
The first thing we did, as soon as the machine released the first sequences, was to publish them on the web.
We published them and appealed for help.
And help came!
Quickly, many people contacted us, surprised by the data we had published.
Some of the world's leading infectious disease specialists were part of our community.
We were working together virtually, sharing regular calls, trying to track the virus minute by minute, to see how to stop it.
There are so many ways to form such communities.
Everyone, when the epidemic began to spread globally, wanted to learn, participate, and engage.
Everyone wanted to play a role.
The number of volunteers was incredible, and the Internet connected us all.
Can you imagine that instead of being afraid of each other, we said, "OK, let's go, working together,
We will defeat this virus. »
The problem was that the data we were using, when searching the web, was too limited for our purpose.
A lot of opportunities are wasted in these cases.
So when the outbreak started in Kenema, we had 106 patient clinical records, and we made them public.
In our lab, we demonstrated that, armed with these 106 records, we could teach our computers to predict Ebola with about 100% accuracy.
We have developed an application that gives access to this information to on-site healthcare workers.
Unfortunately, 106 cases are not enough to consolidate and validate the data.
So we were waiting for more data.
But we were still waiting for the data.
We are still waiting, confined to our silos, instead of working together.
This situation is no longer tolerable.
You, all of you, can no longer accept this.
Our lives are at stake.
Many people lost their lives, health workers, including colleagues who were dear to me. Five colleagues lost their lives: Mbalu Fonnie, Alex Moigboi, Dr. Humarr Khan, Alice Koroma and Mohamed Fullah.
These are just five of many others in Kenema and beyond, dead, while the world waited and we worked, quietly and separately.
Ebola, like all threats to humanity, is fueled by mistrust, confusion and division.
As we build barriers between us, the virus grows.
Unlike all other threats, in the face of Ebola, we are all equal.
We are all in this together.
Ebola is on the threshold of all of us.
And so in this place, we share the same vulnerabilities, strengths, fears and hopes, I hope that we can work together and with pleasure.
One of my former students was reading a book about Sierra Leone, and she discovered that the term "Kenema", the hospital where we work, in Sierra Leone, comes from Mende's quote for "clear as a river, translucent and open to the eyes".
It meant a lot to us because, without knowing it, we had always believed that to honour individuals at Kenema, we had to work openly and together.
We have to do it.
We must all demand of ourselves and others to be open to others, when an epidemic occurs, and to fight it together.
Because this is neither the first Ebola outbreak, nor the last, and there are many other pathogens lurking around us, like the Lassa virus.
The next outbreak could affect a city of millions of people.
It could start there and be transmitted by air.
It could even be disseminated intentionally.
I know it's scary, I understand... But I also know, this experience proves to us, that we have the technology and the ability to defeat, to defeat and get ahead of other viruses.
But this is only possible if we collaborate in joy.
For Dr. Khan, and for all those who gave their lives, on the front, in this fight with us, let us stand with them in this struggle. Always.
Let us not leave the world with the scars of the destruction caused by a virus. Let us illuminate it with the brilliance of billions of hearts and minds working in unity.
Thank you.
